<DOC><DOCNO> AP881214-0251 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-14-88 0847EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-Belgium-Banking     12-14 0221</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Belgium-Banking,0233</SECOND><HEAD>Belgium Raises All Banking Rates</HEAD><DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Belgium's central bank boosted all keybanking interest rates by 0.25 percentage points Wednesday,reflecting the growing trend toward higher rates in theinternational markets.   The Belgian National Bank Wednesday said the discount rate wasraised to 7.5 percent and the Lombard rate to 7.75 percent.   The discount rate is the interest the central bank charges onloans to member commercial banks.The Lombard rate is what the banksare charged for supplemental borrowings in which securities are usedas collateral.   The National Bank had announced earlier it was raising one-, two-and three-month treasury bills.   The three-month rate, considered the most important in Belgianbanking, was raised to 7.4 percent from 7.15 percent, the one-monthrate to 7.35 from 7.1 percent and the two-month rate to 7.4 from7.15 percent.   All the moves take effect on Thursday.   The National Bank said the rate changes came ``in recognition ofthe recent evolution of interest rates on the internationalmarkets.''   Short-term rate levels have been rising in recent weeks in manyindustrial countries, prompting speculation that both the WestGerman Bundesbank and the U.S. Federal Reserve might raise key ratessoon.   Strong economic growth in major industrialized countries hasgiven rise to fears of a resurgence of inflation in many quarters.</TEXT></DOC>